name: Kepler-286
scenarioDescription:
The Kepler-286 Exoplanetary System

Kepler-286 is a star with 0.7550000000000001 times the mass of the Sun, and 0.86 times its radius. It is located 4131.35 light years away from the solar system.

Kepler-286 is known to have 4 exoplanets in orbit around it.

Kepler-286 b

Kepler-286 b was discovered by the Kepler observatory using the transit method. Its discovery was announced in 2014-03. Its semi-major axis is 0.03 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. It takes 1.80 Earth days to complete an orbit around its host star, Kepler-286.

The mass of Kepler-286 b is 1.63 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-286 b is 1.24 that of Earth. At 1.63 Earth masses, Kepler-286 b is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.
